<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8" standalone="yes"?><rss version="2.0" xmlns:atom="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom" xmlns:content="http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/"><channel><title>Algebra on Script Adults</title><link>https://katsuragicsl.github.io/tags/algebra/</link><description>Recent content in Algebra on Script Adults</description><image><title>Script Adults</title><url>https://katsuragicsl.github.io/images/papermod-cover.png</url><link>https://katsuragicsl.github.io/images/papermod-cover.png</link></image><generator>Hugo -- 0.140.0</generator><language>en-us</language><lastBuildDate>Fri, 01 Aug 2025 13:29:15 +0800</lastBuildDate><atom:link href="https://katsuragicsl.github.io/tags/algebra/index.xml" rel="self" type="application/rss+xml"/><item><title>The double dual trick to construct a better object from the existing one</title><link>https://katsuragicsl.github.io/blogs/mathematics/the-double-dual-trick-to-construct-better-object-from-the-existing-one/</link><pubDate>Thu, 31 Jul 2025 23:28:34 +0800</pubDate><guid>https://katsuragicsl.github.io/blogs/mathematics/the-double-dual-trick-to-construct-better-object-from-the-existing-one/</guid><description>&lt;h3 id="stonečech-compactification">Stone–Čech compactification&lt;/h3>
&lt;p>One of the proof of the Stone–Čech compactification is to consider the continuous functions from a given topological space $X$ to $[0, 1]$.&lt;/p>
&lt;p>Crux 1: constructing $[0, 1]^{C}$&lt;/p>
&lt;p>Let $C$ be the space of all continuous functions from $X$ to $[0, 1]$, consider $[0, 1]^{C}$, there is a natural map from $X$ to $[0, 1]^{C}$: for each $x \in X$, define $\phi(x) = f \mapsto f(x)$. With product topology $\phi$ is continuous. Also by Tychonnof&amp;rsquo;s theorem $[0, 1]^{C}$ is compact. Now the closure of the image is obviously compact Hausdorff, and it satisfies a nice property: any continuous map $f : X \to [0, 1]$ extends uniquely to a continuous map $\overline{\phi(X)} \to [0,1]$: for any $\phi(x)$, it has to map to $f(x)$!&lt;/p></description></item><item><title>Amazed by how ring theory can be linked up to topology</title><link>https://katsuragicsl.github.io/blogs/mathematics/linking-up-ring-and-topology/</link><pubDate>Thu, 26 Jun 2025 01:37:20 +0800</pubDate><guid>https://katsuragicsl.github.io/blogs/mathematics/linking-up-ring-and-topology/</guid><description>&lt;p>I am reviewing some fundamental algebra, and I just learnt something beautifully suggesting the connection of ring theory and geometry, which made me eager to learn some algebraic geometry (which I was not very interested when I was in undergrad). It is an exercise in Aluffi&amp;rsquo;s book&lt;sup id="fnref:1">&lt;a href="#fn:1" class="footnote-ref" role="doc-noteref">1&lt;/a>&lt;/sup>.&lt;/p>
&lt;p>Lets&amp;rsquo; jump into it.&lt;/p>
&lt;h3 id="the-problem">The problem&lt;/h3>
&lt;blockquote>
&lt;p>Let $K$ be a compact topological space, and let $R$ be the ring of continuous real-valued functions on $K$, with addition and multiplication defined pointwise. &lt;br>
(i) For $p \in K$, let $M_p = \{f \in R | f(p) = 0\}$. Prove that $M_p$ is a maximal ideal in $R$. &lt;br>
(ii) Prove that if $f_1, \dots , f_r \in R$ have no common zeros, then $(f1, \dots , fr)$ = $(1)$. &lt;br>
(Hint: Consider $f^2_1 + \dots + f^2_r$ .) &lt;br>
(iii) Prove that every maximal ideal $M$ in $R$ is of the form $M_p$ for some $p \in K$. &lt;br>
(Hint: You will use the compactness of $K$ and (ii).)&lt;/p></description></item><item><title>A more intuitive explanation of Burnside's lemma</title><link>https://katsuragicsl.github.io/blogs/mathematics/a-more-intuitive-explanation-of-burnside-lemma/</link><pubDate>Thu, 10 Apr 2025 00:56:29 +0800</pubDate><guid>https://katsuragicsl.github.io/blogs/mathematics/a-more-intuitive-explanation-of-burnside-lemma/</guid><description>&lt;style type="text/css">
